===Verb===
{{en-verb|accompan|ies}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To go with or attend as a companion or associate; to keep company with; to go along with.
#* '''1804''' [[w:Richard Glover (poet)|Richard Glover]]:
#*: The Persian dames, […] / In sumptuous cars, '''accompanied''' his march.
#* '''1581''', {{w|Philip Sidney}}, ''An Apology of Poetry, or a Defense of Poesy'', Book I:
#*: They are never alone that are '''accompanied''' with noble thoughts.
#* {{quote-text|year=1979|author={{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}|title=The History of England|passage=He was '''accompanied''' by two carts filled with wounded rebels.}}
#: {{ux|en|Geoffrey '''accompanied''' the group on their pilgrimage.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To supplement with; add to.
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=5
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=He was thinking; but the glory of the song, the swell from the great organ, the clustered lights, […], the height and vastness of this noble fane, its antiquity and its strength—all these things seemed to have their part as causes of the thrilling emotion that '''accompanied''' his thoughts.}}
# {{senseid|en|to perform an accompanying part next to another instrument}}{{lb|en|intransitive|music}} To perform an accompanying part or parts in a [[composition]].
# {{lb|en|transitive|music}} To perform an accompanying part next to another instrument.
#: {{ux|en|The strings were '''accompanied''' by two woodwinds.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To associate in a company; to keep company.
#* {{rfdate}} Holland:
#*: Men say that they will drive away one another, […] and not '''accompany''' together.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[cohabit]] (with).
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To cohabit with; to coexist with; occur with.
#: {{rfquotek|Sir T. Herbert}}
{{rfex|en|the obsolete cases}}
